05049nam a22008055i 9786155225512DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222013hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97861552255127 a10.1515/97861552255122doi  a(DE-B1597)633610  a(OCoLC)1338020571  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 7aHIS0050002bisacsh1 aKõll, Anu Mai, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Village and the Class War :bAnti-Kulak Campaign in Estonia 1944-49 /cAnu Mai Kõll. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistorical Studies in Eastern Europe and Eurasia00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Tables and Graphs -- tList of Photographs -- tPreface -- tChapter 1 The Land Question in Estonia -- tChapter 2 Soviet Repression as a Special Case of State Violence Chapter 3 The Anti-kulak Campaign -- tChapter 3 The Anti-kulak Campaign -- tChapter 4 Inventing Kulaks -- tChapter 5 Participation at the Local Level -- tChapter 6 Epilogue of March 1949 -- tChapter 7 The Grammar of Terror -- tAppendix I -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBefore collectivization of agriculture in Estonia, “kulaks” (better-off farmers) were persecuted and many of them were finally deported in March 1949. This book is situated on the local level; the aim is to understand what these processes meant from the perspective of the Estonian rural population, a kind of study that has been missing so far. Analyzes the mechanisms of repression, applying new aspects. Repression was mainly conducted through a bureaucratic process where individual denunciations were not even necessary. The main tool of persecution was a screening of the rural population with the help of records, censuses and local knowledge, in order to identify, or invent, “kulak families”. Moreover, in the Estonian sources, the World War II history of each individual was a crucial part of screenings. The prisoners of war of the Red Army, held in camps in Estonia, played an unexpected part in this campaign. Another result is a so far neglected wave of peaceful resistance as the kulak identifications were challenged in 1947-48. This has not been addressed in the existing literature. The results mainly answer the question “how” this process worked, whereas the question ”why” finds hypothetical responses in the life trajectories of actors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCollective farms -- Estonia -- History. 0aCollective farmszEstoniaxHistory. 0aCollectivization of agriculture -- Estonia -- History. 0aCollectivization of agriculture -- Soviet Union -- History. 0aCollectivization of agriculturezEstoniaxHistory. 0aCollectivization of agriculturezSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aCommunism -- Estonia -- History -- 20th century. 0aCommunismzEstoniaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLand tenure -- Estonia -- History. 0aLand tenurezEstoniaxHistory. 0aPeasants -- Estonia -- History -- 20th century. 0aPeasantszEstoniaxHistoryy20th century. 0aState-sponsored terrorism -- Estonia -- History. 0aState-sponsored terrorismzEstoniaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Baltic States.2bisacsh  aCollectivization, Agriculture, Communism, Estonia, Prisoners of war, Rural conditions, Soviet Union.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978615522551240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155225512423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155225512/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Packag